words alone. [CLS] [SEP] For example, some YES-NO-QUESTiONS have word sequences identical to those of STATEMENTS, but can often be distinguished by their final F0 rise. [CLS] [SEP] A detailed study aimed at automatic prosodic classification of DAs in the Switchboard domain is available in a companion paper (Shriberg et al. 1998). [CLS] [SEP] Here we investigate the interaction of prosodic models with the dialogue grammar and the word-based DA models discussed above. [CLS] [SEP] We also touch briefly on alternative machine learning models for prosodic features. [CLS] [SEP] 5.2.1 Prosodic Features. [CLS] [SEP] Prosodic DA classification was based on a large set of features computed automatically from the waveform, without reference to word or phone information. [CLS] [SEP] The features can be broadly grouped as referring to duration (e.g., utterance duration, with and without pauses), pauses (e.g., total and mean of nonspeech regions exceeding 100 ms), pitch (e.g., mean and range of F0 over utterance, slope of F0 regression line), energy (e.g., mean and range of RMS energy, same for signal-to- logarithm was -d1 logP(Ai]Wi) + logP(WilUi) -~lWil. [CLS] [SEP] We found this approach to give better results than the standard multiplication of logP(W) by ,L Note that for selecting the best hypothesis in a recognizer only the relative magnitudes of the score weights matter; however, for the summation in Equation 6 the absolute values become important. [CLS] [SEP] The parameter values for )~ and # were those used by the standard recognizer; they were not specifically optimized for the DA classification task. [CLS] [SEP] ~ 23.403 an utt < 0.3"/~U >= 0.3"/17 ~ Figure 3 Decision tree for the classification of BACKCHANNELS (B) and AGREEMENTS (A). [CLS] [SEP] Each node is labeled with the majority class for that node, as well as the posterior probabilities of the two classes. [CLS] [SEP] The following features are queried in the tree: number of frames in continuous (> 1 s) speech r