ive results, these should be interpreted as informative datapoints only, and not as fair comparisons between algorithms. [CLS] [SEP] Previous research on DA modeling has generally focused on task-oriented dialogue, with three tasks in particular garnering much of the research effort. [CLS] [SEP] The Map Task corpus (Anderson et al. 1991; Bard et al. 1995) consists of conversations between two speakers with slightly different maps of an imaginary territory. [CLS] [SEP] Their task is to help one speaker reproduce a route drawn only on the other speaker's map, all without being able to see each other's maps. [CLS] [SEP] Of the DA modeling algorithms described below, Taylor et al. (1998) and Wright (1998) were based on Map Task. [CLS] [SEP] The VERBMOBIL corpus consists of two-party scheduling dialogues. [CLS] [SEP] A number of the DA m6deling algorithms described below were developed for VERBMOBIL, including those of Mast et al. (1996), Warnke et al. (1997), Reithinger et al. (1996), Reithinger and Klesen (1997), and Samuel, Carberry, and VijayShanker (1998). [CLS] [SEP] The ATR Conference corpus is a subset of a larger ATR Dialogue database consisting of simulated dialogues between a secretary and a questioner at international conferences. [CLS] [SEP] Researchers using this corpus include Nagata (1992), Nagata and Morimoto (1993, 1994), and Kita et al. (1996). [CLS] [SEP] Table 13 shows the most commonly used versions of the tag sets from those three tasks. [CLS] [SEP] As discussed earlier, these domains differ from the Switchboard corpus in being task-oriented. [CLS] [SEP] Their tag sets are also generally smaller, but some of the same problems of balance occur. [CLS] [SEP] For example, in the Map Task domain, 33% of the words occur in 1 of the 12 DAs 0NSTRUCT). [CLS] [SEP] Table 14 shows the approximate size of the corpora, the tag set, and tag estimation accuracy rates for various recent models of DA prediction. [CLS] [SEP] The results summarized in the table also 